In [[atomic physics]], '''exoelectron emission''' (EE) is a weak [[electron]] emission, appearing only from pretreated (irradiated, deformed etc.) objects.<ref name=Oster1999>{{citation | last = Oster | first =  L. | year = 1999 | title = Classification of Exoelectron Emission Mechanisms | journal = Physica Status Solidi A | volume = 174 | issue = 2 | pages = 431 | doi = 10.1002/(SICI)1521-396X(199908)174:2<431::AID-PSSA431>3.0.CO;2-Z | last2 = Yaskolko | first2 = V. | last3 = Haddad | first3 = J. |bibcode = 1999PSSAR.174..431O }}</ref><ref name=Gerasimov1976>{{citation | last = Gerasimov | first =  A. B. | year = 1976 | title = On the physical mechanism of exoelectron emission | journal = Physica Status Solidi A | volume = 35 | issue = 2 | pages = K131 | doi = 10.1002/pssa.2210350256 | last2 = Dolidze | first2 = G. M. | last3 = Mizandari | first3 = L. A. | last4 = Tsertsvadze | first4 = A. A. |bibcode = 1976PSSAR..35..131G }}</ref> The pretreatment ("excitation") turns the objects into an unequilibrial state. EE accompanies the relaxation of these unequilibria. The relaxation can be stimulated e.g. by slight heating or longwave illumination, not causing emission from untreated samples. Accordingly, thermo- and  photostimulated EE (TSEE, PSEE) are distinguished. Thus, EE is an electron emission analogue of such optical phenomena as [[phosphorescence]], thermo- and [[photostimulated luminescence]].

